WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.435 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.435 --> 00:00:03.409 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.409 --> 00:00:04.383 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.383 --> 00:00:07.792 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.792 --> 00:00:11.510 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:14.610 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So at the
end of last lecture,

00:00:14.610 --> 00:00:19.450 align:middle line:84%
we start talking
about this propagator.

00:00:19.450 --> 00:00:29.260 align:middle line:90%


00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:37.030 align:middle line:84%
So in non-relativistic
quantum mechanics,

00:00:37.030 --> 00:00:45.420 align:middle line:84%
in the Heisenberg picture, we
can introduce this position

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:52.080 align:middle line:84%
eigenvector corresponding to
the eigenvalue of the position

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:58.050 align:middle line:84%
operator at time t
with eigenvalue x.

00:00:58.050 --> 00:01:02.130 align:middle line:84%
And then from this object, you
can construct a propagator.

00:01:02.130 --> 00:01:07.680 align:middle line:90%


00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:09.360 align:middle line:84%
So this object is
powerful if you

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.180 align:middle line:84%
know how to compute this
object, because if you

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:17.310 align:middle line:84%
load the function at
t prime, and then by--

00:01:17.310 --> 00:01:21.630 align:middle line:84%
yeah, by just integrate
it with this object,

00:01:21.630 --> 00:01:25.170 align:middle line:84%
and then you can find your
function at a later time.

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:29.610 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a powerful object
in non-relativistic quantum

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:31.950 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

00:01:31.950 --> 00:01:36.150 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can ask what
are the analogous objects--

00:01:36.150 --> 00:01:43.800 align:middle line:84%
say whether they exist analogous
object in field theory.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:55.710 align:middle line:84%
But in QFT, there
is no natural way

00:01:55.710 --> 00:02:15.760 align:middle line:84%
to define a localized
state such as--

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:19.750 align:middle line:84%
so there's no counterpart
of this object.

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:21.910 align:middle line:84%
So one reason is
that now there's

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:23.620 align:middle line:90%
no position operator anymore.

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:27.220 align:middle line:84%
So remember, now, x
is actually a label--

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:31.520 align:middle line:90%
no longer a operator.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:34.430 align:middle line:84%
It's the phi is the
operator. x is just a label.

00:02:34.430 --> 00:02:37.490 align:middle line:84%
So there's no-- in
quantum field theory,

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:40.840 align:middle line:90%
there's no position operator.

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:44.890 align:middle line:90%


00:02:44.890 --> 00:02:47.800 align:middle line:84%
So you cannot-- and
then you cannot define--

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:50.920 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so the position
operator, then you can--

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:54.010 align:middle line:84%
no natural way to
define the eigenvector

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:58.310 align:middle line:90%
associated with localized state.

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:00.205 align:middle line:84%
And there's also a
fundamental barrier--

00:03:00.205 --> 00:03:03.560 align:middle line:90%


00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:06.280 align:middle line:84%
there's a fundamental
contradiction

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:08.800 align:middle line:90%
with Lorentz symmetry.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:12.070 align:middle line:84%
So there's also a
fundamental barrier--

00:03:12.070 --> 00:03:21.675 align:middle line:84%
fundamental obstruction
from Lorentz symmetry.

00:03:21.675 --> 00:03:34.750 align:middle line:90%


00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:42.480 align:middle line:90%
So you can show that localized--

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:56.900 align:middle line:84%
you can show a
localized state in space

00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:00.350 align:middle line:90%
is not Lorentz covariant.

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:07.370 align:middle line:90%


00:04:07.370 --> 00:04:09.050 align:middle line:90%
So this does not--

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:16.100 align:middle line:84%
so suppose-- yeah, you can do
this by proof by contradiction.

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:28.280 align:middle line:84%
Suppose they exist-- there
exist states like some states--

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:34.260 align:middle line:90%


00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:36.750 align:middle line:90%
say, x t.

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:44.460 align:middle line:84%
So by definition, a local
state should satisfy in--

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:52.025 align:middle line:84%
if you evaluate them
at the same time,

00:04:52.025 --> 00:04:56.930 align:middle line:84%
then that should be
proportional to delta function

00:04:56.930 --> 00:04:59.480 align:middle line:84%
because that's by definition
what it means what

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.190 align:middle line:90%
we mean by a localized state--

00:05:01.190 --> 00:05:03.760 align:middle line:90%
localized at the point.

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:06.020 align:middle line:84%
And that's the property
satisfied by this.

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:08.578 align:middle line:84%
If you set t prime equal
to t, and then this

00:05:08.578 --> 00:05:09.620 align:middle line:90%
will be a delta function.

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:13.540 align:middle line:90%


00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:19.210 align:middle line:84%
But now, suppose you
can define such a state,

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:21.640 align:middle line:84%
but then this notion cannot
be covariant defined.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:24.970 align:middle line:84%
It's because this is
not a covariant object.

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:27.670 align:middle line:84%
So the three-dimensional
spatial delta

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:30.850 align:middle line:84%
function that does
not transform nicely

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.630 align:middle line:90%
under Lorentz transformation.

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:39.430 align:middle line:84%
And so you can show
that if you act--

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:48.880 align:middle line:84%
suppose U lambda is
the unitary operator

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.530 align:middle line:84%
generating a Lorentz
transformation,

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:54.670 align:middle line:90%
which we discussed last time.

00:05:54.670 --> 00:05:58.430 align:middle line:90%
If you have the momentum--

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:02.780 align:middle line:84%
if you have the generated
Lorentz transformation.

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:10.180 align:middle line:84%
And then you can show that
the U lambda acting on x and t

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:16.890 align:middle line:84%
is not the same as the
lambda x and the lambda t.

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:19.770 align:middle line:84%
So lambda x and lambda T
denotes a Lorentz transformation

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:21.750 align:middle line:90%
of this vector.

00:06:21.750 --> 00:06:23.670 align:middle line:84%
Here, I'm using a
shorthand notation.

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:27.580 align:middle line:90%


00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:30.720 align:middle line:84%
So lambda-- x means the
Lorentz transformation acts

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:33.120 align:middle line:84%
on x, and here, means the
Lorentz transformation

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:36.200 align:middle line:90%
acts on t.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.430 align:middle line:84%
And you actually will do
this explicitly in your pset.

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:43.660 align:middle line:90%
You will check this explicitly.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:47.030 align:middle line:90%
This does not transform.

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:51.420 align:middle line:84%
So this cannot be a
covariant concept.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:56.100 align:middle line:84%
So that means that you can
most define in some frame,

00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:59.400 align:middle line:84%
but if you change your
frame, and then this state

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:01.350 align:middle line:90%
is no longer localized.

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:07.800 align:middle line:84%
So this concept is
not the Lorentz--

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:11.670 align:middle line:84%
it's not compatible
with Lorentz symmetry.

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:21.660 align:middle line:84%
So the closest analog you
can define in field theory--

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:25.010 align:middle line:90%


00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:27.500 align:middle line:90%
closest-- sorry, not closed--

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:35.230 align:middle line:84%
closest analog in QFT in
field theory is this object.

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:41.090 align:middle line:84%
So let's define an object
x could be defined by--

00:07:41.090 --> 00:07:43.970 align:middle line:84%
so again, whenever I
write something like x,

00:07:43.970 --> 00:07:47.300 align:middle line:84%
you should view this as a
shorthand for the full vector

00:07:47.300 --> 00:07:51.150 align:middle line:90%
including both space and time.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:55.890 align:middle line:84%
And so this second,
define an object by this--

00:07:55.890 --> 00:07:59.580 align:middle line:84%
acting-- let's just consider--
suppose we have a real scalar

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:00.750 align:middle line:90%
field theory.

00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:02.960 align:middle line:84%
So for example, let's just
consider real scalar field

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:03.460 align:middle line:90%
theory.

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:05.830 align:middle line:84%
So we can define an
object like this.

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:10.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is the closest we can
get into a position eigenstate.

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:13.410 align:middle line:90%


00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:15.520 align:middle line:90%
And then-- yeah, its conjugate.

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:19.020 align:middle line:90%
Then it's given by phi.

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So phi is a hermitian,
because it's real,

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:23.440 align:middle line:90%
so it's a hermitian operator.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:26.790 align:middle line:84%
So now, you can check
this object by definition

00:08:26.790 --> 00:08:30.120 align:middle line:84%
because phi is a scalar
field will transforms nicely

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:32.679 align:middle line:90%
on the Lorentz transformation.

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:37.309 align:middle line:84%
And the vacuum is invariant
under Lorentz transformation.

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:40.870 align:middle line:84%
And so this object
actually transforms nicely.

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:48.830 align:middle line:84%
So under Lorentz transformation,
x actually it goes to lambda x.

00:08:48.830 --> 00:08:53.590 align:middle line:84%
So this object actually
transforms nicely.

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.760 align:middle line:90%


00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:59.730 align:middle line:84%
But you can also ask, what is
the overlap between these two

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:03.900 align:middle line:84%
such kind of position eigenstate
if we call this quoted position

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:05.520 align:middle line:90%
eigenstate?

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:08.910 align:middle line:84%
So now let's
consider the overlap

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:12.210 align:middle line:90%
between two such states.

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:14.940 align:middle line:90%
And then this will be given by--

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:20.460 align:middle line:84%
from this definition will
be given by 0 phi x and phi

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:24.790 align:middle line:90%
x prime on there.

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:29.540 align:middle line:90%


00:09:29.540 --> 00:09:35.540 align:middle line:84%
So it's given by the
expectation value of x times phi

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:39.950 align:middle line:84%
x prime between
the vacuum states

00:09:39.950 --> 00:09:42.440 align:middle line:90%
just from the definition.

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:44.410 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we say
this is the closest

00:09:44.410 --> 00:09:48.420 align:middle line:84%
analog is because even
though this state is

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:52.320 align:middle line:84%
Lorentz covariant, but this
state is not localized.

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:55.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you want a
state to be localized,

00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:59.550 align:middle line:84%
this has to be proportional
to delta function

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:01.830 align:middle line:84%
when you take the
them at the same time.

00:10:01.830 --> 00:10:03.210 align:middle line:90%
But now you can show--

00:10:03.210 --> 00:10:06.870 align:middle line:84%
so this is the object we
can compute explicitly,

00:10:06.870 --> 00:10:10.650 align:middle line:84%
because we already
solved the phi completely

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:12.060 align:middle line:90%
in terms of a and a dagger.

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:15.510 align:middle line:84%
You can just plug-in here to
compute this object explicitly,

00:10:15.510 --> 00:10:21.210 align:middle line:84%
and we will do a towards
the end of today's lecture.

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:23.470 align:middle line:84%
Here, let me just
tell you the results.

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:26.400 align:middle line:84%
So you can see that
this guy actually

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:32.850 align:middle line:84%
is non-zero for t
equal to t prime

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:37.740 align:middle line:90%
and x not equal to x prime.

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:41.160 align:middle line:84%
So that means this is not--
this means that this cannot be

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:42.250 align:middle line:90%
a delta function.

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:45.180 align:middle line:84%
So when you evaluate
them at the same time,

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:47.140 align:middle line:84%
if it's a localized
state, then it should be

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:49.240 align:middle line:90%
proportional to delta function.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:51.520 align:middle line:90%
But this is not the case.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:56.410 align:middle line:84%
So this object is
not quite localized,

00:10:56.410 --> 00:11:01.000 align:middle line:84%
but we will see actually in
some sense, it's localized,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.570 align:middle line:84%
and we will see in what
sense later when we

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:08.210 align:middle line:90%
compute this object explicitly.

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:10.580 align:middle line:84%
So right now, let's
just say the conclusion

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:13.250 align:middle line:90%
that this is not localized.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:14.900 align:middle line:90%
So this is not--

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:18.305 align:middle line:84%
so this means this is
not a localized state.

00:11:18.305 --> 00:11:37.020 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:38.630 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:44.380 align:middle line:90%
So heuristically, we can say--

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:52.915 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so let me just
make a side remark here.

00:11:52.915 --> 00:11:58.790 align:middle line:90%


00:11:58.790 --> 00:12:03.880 align:middle line:84%
So if we-- so as we say, this
is not a position eigenstate.

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:07.660 align:middle line:84%
But if we treat it as
some kind of approximation

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:10.270 align:middle line:84%
to the position
eigenstate, and then we

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:16.180 align:middle line:84%
can talk about the wave
function of a particle.

00:12:16.180 --> 00:12:18.580 align:middle line:90%
So now let's suppose--

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:31.860 align:middle line:84%
so given a single
particle state, psi--

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:35.700 align:middle line:84%
so psi would be say some
kind of superposition,

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:37.190 align:middle line:90%
which we wrote last time--

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:41.120 align:middle line:84%
so some arbitrary superposition
of the single particle state

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:43.590 align:middle line:90%
integrate over the momentum.

00:12:43.590 --> 00:12:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And then we can define
its wave function.

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:52.420 align:middle line:90%


00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:58.980 align:middle line:84%
So I put this
function as a quote

00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:07.180 align:middle line:84%
as psi x equal to just
overlap between the psi

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:11.950 align:middle line:90%
and this x object.

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:16.600 align:middle line:84%
And then this is given by
just from that definition--

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:23.590 align:middle line:90%
just given by 0 phi x psi.

00:13:23.590 --> 00:13:29.990 align:middle line:90%
So we can define a function--

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:33.630 align:middle line:84%
so this is closest analog
you can define a wave

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:36.980 align:middle line:84%
function for particle
in the field theory

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:38.360 align:middle line:90%
is to use this object.

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:41.110 align:middle line:90%


00:13:41.110 --> 00:13:43.150 align:middle line:90%
And now, you can check--

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:47.530 align:middle line:84%
so it's a very simple exercise
for you to check yourself.

00:13:47.530 --> 00:13:51.370 align:middle line:84%
So if I just take this to
be the pure momentum state--

00:13:51.370 --> 00:13:57.850 align:middle line:84%
say, for example, if I take
psi to be the pure momentum

00:13:57.850 --> 00:13:59.260 align:middle line:90%
state of k--

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:04.810 align:middle line:84%
remember, this notation k
is the square root 2 omega

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:08.950 align:middle line:90%
k on this state.

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:11.320 align:middle line:84%
So this is the pure
momentum state.

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:16.540 align:middle line:84%
And then if you calculate this
object, and then you get--

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:23.230 align:middle line:84%
then k x then just
becomes 0 phi x k.

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:24.460 align:middle line:90%
Now, you can again--

00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:26.980 align:middle line:84%
you know explicitly
how phi expressed

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:29.110 align:middle line:84%
in terms of a and
a dagger, and you

00:14:29.110 --> 00:14:32.230 align:middle line:84%
know how this is
obtained from the vacuum

00:14:32.230 --> 00:14:33.610 align:middle line:90%
by acting a dagger on it.

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:35.680 align:middle line:84%
You can just
compute this object.

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:38.020 align:middle line:90%
So take a couple of minutes.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:42.400 align:middle line:84%
And you can also just
essentially guess the answer.

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:44.065 align:middle line:84%
So this just gives
you the plane wave--

00:14:44.065 --> 00:14:47.470 align:middle line:90%


00:14:47.470 --> 00:14:49.720 align:middle line:84%
just gives you an
initial plane wave.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:54.640 align:middle line:84%
So with your energy
are given by omega k.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.080 align:middle line:84%
So you just get the
plane wave function.

00:14:57.080 --> 00:14:59.287 align:middle line:84%
So in this sense, it's
like a wave function.

00:14:59.287 --> 00:15:01.120 align:middle line:84%
It makes sense to call
it the wave function.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:06.915 align:middle line:90%


00:15:06.915 --> 00:15:08.550 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:15:08.550 --> 00:15:12.090 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So in this state here,
we call this the wave function.

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:13.770 align:middle line:84%
If we take it, and
you multiply it

00:15:13.770 --> 00:15:16.040 align:middle line:90%
by its own complex transpose--

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:18.480 align:middle line:84%
can we interpret it
as a probability?

00:15:18.480 --> 00:15:21.420 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, this is the
comment I'm going to make now.

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:24.210 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, this is a good question.

00:15:24.210 --> 00:15:26.610 align:middle line:90%
So we cannot really--

00:15:26.610 --> 00:15:31.560 align:middle line:90%
so we cannot-- so in general--

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:49.850 align:middle line:84%
so psi x prime, in general,
cannot be interpreted as giving

00:15:49.850 --> 00:16:05.445 align:middle line:84%
the probability of
the particle at x.

00:16:05.445 --> 00:16:12.060 align:middle line:90%


00:16:12.060 --> 00:16:15.270 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we cannot do
that is because this is not--

00:16:15.270 --> 00:16:18.995 align:middle line:84%
because x is not the
genuine position eigenstate.

00:16:18.995 --> 00:16:20.370 align:middle line:84%
And also in quantum
field theory,

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:22.730 align:middle line:90%
we don't really have this--

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:26.450 align:middle line:84%
we don't really have this
proper sense of talking about--

00:16:26.450 --> 00:16:30.470 align:middle line:84%
you cannot really-- in general,
you cannot separate the single

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:33.230 align:middle line:84%
particle with multiple
particle exactly, in general,

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:34.910 align:middle line:90%
in quantum field theory.

00:16:34.910 --> 00:16:40.320 align:middle line:84%
In free theory, you can because
there is no interaction.

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:44.390 align:middle line:90%
But in general, you cannot.

00:16:44.390 --> 00:16:46.280 align:middle line:84%
So the reason this
is a side remark

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:49.160 align:middle line:84%
is that this is
often used by people,

00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:53.390 align:middle line:84%
and they just call
it a wave function.

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:54.920 align:middle line:84%
But you should
keep in mind what's

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:58.640 align:middle line:84%
the content of this
object, and it's not

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:02.510 align:middle line:84%
something you can
actually rigorously define

00:17:02.510 --> 00:17:06.380 align:middle line:84%
both mathematically and
physically as a wave function.

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:11.290 align:middle line:90%


00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:12.405 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:17:12.405 --> 00:17:14.905 align:middle line:90%


00:17:14.905 --> 00:17:16.280 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So could
you explain how

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:19.430 align:middle line:90%
