00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:21.819 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Oh, you
just calculate.

00:17:21.819 --> 00:17:24.609 align:middle line:90%


00:17:24.609 --> 00:17:28.300 align:middle line:84%
But it's very easy to see how
you get that because remember,

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:30.070 align:middle line:90%
phi x is--

00:17:30.070 --> 00:17:36.440 align:middle line:84%
phi x can be expanded in terms
of a u plus a dagger u star.

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:39.790 align:middle line:84%
And the k is obtained
by a dagger acting on 0.

00:17:39.790 --> 00:17:44.710 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, just a and a dagger
part, and give you this object,

00:17:44.710 --> 00:17:48.500 align:middle line:84%
and a part proportional to
u, and that's how you get it.

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:52.570 align:middle line:90%


00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:53.070 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:17:53.070 --> 00:17:57.780 align:middle line:90%


00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:02.310 align:middle line:84%
So when we compute
this object explicitly,

00:18:02.310 --> 00:18:05.700 align:middle line:84%
you will get a
more precise sense

00:18:05.700 --> 00:18:10.470 align:middle line:84%
what I mean that this
is an approximation.

00:18:10.470 --> 00:18:12.340 align:middle line:84%
You will get a
more precise sense.

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:14.610 align:middle line:90%
And so this--

00:18:14.610 --> 00:18:16.548 align:middle line:84%
I'll now defer that a
little bit because I

00:18:16.548 --> 00:18:18.215 align:middle line:84%
want to talk about
something else first.

00:18:18.215 --> 00:18:21.690 align:middle line:90%


00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:22.190 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:18:22.190 --> 00:18:23.030 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:27.400 align:middle line:90%


00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:32.760 align:middle line:84%
So here-- so this actually
is a very important object.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:34.680 align:middle line:90%
Forget about this definition.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:38.730 align:middle line:84%
So this object-- yeah, let me
just write this object again.

00:18:38.730 --> 00:18:41.570 align:middle line:90%
So this G plus--

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:49.010 align:middle line:84%
so this object 0 phi
x and phi x prime 0--

00:18:49.010 --> 00:18:58.190 align:middle line:84%
so we motivated as this
overlap between these two

00:18:58.190 --> 00:19:00.050 align:middle line:90%
localized states--

00:19:00.050 --> 00:19:02.697 align:middle line:84%
these two approximate
localized states.

00:19:02.697 --> 00:19:04.280 align:middle line:84%
But in quantum field
theory, actually,

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:09.380 align:middle line:84%
this is a very important object,
and actually, we normally

00:19:09.380 --> 00:19:13.760 align:middle line:84%
assign a rotation G
plus with this object.

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:16.910 align:middle line:84%
And so the application
of this object,

00:19:16.910 --> 00:19:19.430 align:middle line:84%
we will not talk
too much about it.

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:21.860 align:middle line:90%
But in condensed matter--

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:24.140 align:middle line:84%
for example, say
in phi, describes

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:26.990 align:middle line:84%
some approximate-- some
continuum description of a spin

00:19:26.990 --> 00:19:27.770 align:middle line:90%
system.

00:19:27.770 --> 00:19:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And then this would be
measure the correlation

00:19:30.500 --> 00:19:33.470 align:middle line:84%
between the spins at
different locations--

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:35.450 align:middle line:84%
at different locations
and different time.

00:19:35.450 --> 00:19:37.733 align:middle line:84%
So this is what people call
the correlation functions.

00:19:37.733 --> 00:19:40.400 align:middle line:84%
And so in condensed matter, this
actually plays a very important

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:43.520 align:middle line:84%
role, and matches
the correlation

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:47.450 align:middle line:84%
between different
physical objects.

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.825 align:middle line:90%
And so here-- so when x--

00:19:50.825 --> 00:19:54.340 align:middle line:90%


00:19:54.340 --> 00:19:59.920 align:middle line:84%
for x and x prime,
at non-equal time--

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:05.460 align:middle line:90%


00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:11.670 align:middle line:84%
in general, phi x and phi
x prime do not commute.

00:20:11.670 --> 00:20:16.270 align:middle line:90%


00:20:16.270 --> 00:20:18.460 align:middle line:84%
Remember our
commutation relation--

00:20:18.460 --> 00:20:20.800 align:middle line:84%
canonical commutation
relation is phi--

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:23.050 align:middle line:84%
phi x and phi x
prime, they commute

00:20:23.050 --> 00:20:25.300 align:middle line:90%
when they at equal time.

00:20:25.300 --> 00:20:29.620 align:middle line:84%
When they are not
equal time, in general,

00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:32.320 align:middle line:90%
they don't have to commute.

00:20:32.320 --> 00:20:35.740 align:middle line:84%
So the ordering here
is actually important.

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:45.940 align:middle line:84%
So the ordering of phi in G
plus is actually important.

00:20:45.940 --> 00:20:52.120 align:middle line:90%


00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:56.410 align:middle line:90%
So if I define some--

00:20:56.410 --> 00:21:00.380 align:middle line:84%
I can consider a lot of objects
with a different ordering.

00:21:00.380 --> 00:21:03.550 align:middle line:84%
Say if I put the
phi x prime first,

00:21:03.550 --> 00:21:07.720 align:middle line:84%
I can also consider this object
for the phi x prime first.

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:10.720 align:middle line:90%


00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:12.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is normally called--

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:15.830 align:middle line:84%
now, this is a different
function in general

00:21:15.830 --> 00:21:18.860 align:middle line:84%
because they don't commute
and we call it G minus.

00:21:18.860 --> 00:21:25.090 align:middle line:90%


00:21:25.090 --> 00:21:29.570 align:middle line:84%
So this is also
appropriately just x prime x.

00:21:29.570 --> 00:21:34.300 align:middle line:84%
So this is the x
prime x and this is

00:21:34.300 --> 00:21:39.950 align:middle line:90%
using that notation is x prime.

00:21:39.950 --> 00:21:43.865 align:middle line:84%
And so in general, G plus and
G minus, they are not the same.

00:21:43.865 --> 00:21:46.520 align:middle line:90%


00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:51.940 align:middle line:84%
So you can also define
some other functions--

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:57.520 align:middle line:84%
say since the phi and phi x
and phi x prime don't commute,

00:21:57.520 --> 00:21:58.720 align:middle line:90%
then you say--

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:01.810 align:middle line:84%
then we can consider
more general orderings.

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:04.840 align:middle line:84%
We can consider the
superposition of these two.

00:22:04.840 --> 00:22:13.050 align:middle line:84%
So you can consider the
retarded function so-called,

00:22:13.050 --> 00:22:18.120 align:middle line:84%
which is defined to be the
theta t minus t prime--

00:22:18.120 --> 00:22:21.110 align:middle line:90%


00:22:21.110 --> 00:22:25.610 align:middle line:84%
the commutator of phi
x and phi x prime.

00:22:25.610 --> 00:22:28.670 align:middle line:90%


00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:33.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is some other
object you can define,

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.220 align:middle line:84%
which is the difference
between the two,

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:41.320 align:middle line:84%
but it only takes value when
t is greater than t prime.

00:22:41.320 --> 00:22:43.930 align:middle line:84%
So when t is smaller than
t prime, then it's 0.

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:48.680 align:middle line:84%
So this is another other
object we often use.

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:53.660 align:middle line:84%
And so this often is denoted
by theta t minus t prime,

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:57.180 align:middle line:84%
and call this object-- this
commutator to be delta t,

00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:00.420 align:middle line:90%
