00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:54.960 align:middle line:84%
when we consider interactions,
and so that's why

00:28:54.960 --> 00:28:57.300 align:middle line:90%
we want to introduce it here.

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And this G plus G minus are
called the Wightman functions.

00:29:02.190 --> 00:29:07.558 align:middle line:90%


00:29:07.558 --> 00:29:09.350 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes, called
the Wightman function.

00:29:09.350 --> 00:29:11.790 align:middle line:84%
The G F is called
the Feynman function.

00:29:11.790 --> 00:29:15.210 align:middle line:84%
So Feynman was the first
person who introduced it.

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:20.200 align:middle line:90%


00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, so G plus G minus
was introduced by other people,

00:29:25.870 --> 00:29:30.510 align:middle line:84%
but Wightman made many
important use of it

00:29:30.510 --> 00:29:32.260 align:middle line:84%
in the early days of
quantum field theory,

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:33.802 align:middle line:84%
so it's called the
Wightman function.

00:29:33.802 --> 00:29:37.460 align:middle line:90%


00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:39.950 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's just study a
little bit the properties

00:29:39.950 --> 00:29:41.360 align:middle line:90%
of those functions.

00:29:41.360 --> 00:29:46.820 align:middle line:84%
So you can also think these
are essentially the simplest

00:29:46.820 --> 00:29:49.130 align:middle line:90%
observables of the system.

00:29:49.130 --> 00:29:51.410 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, if you
think of them as correlation

00:29:51.410 --> 00:29:53.660 align:middle line:84%
functions, and then
that just tells you

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:56.270 align:middle line:84%
the correlation between the
phi at a different point.

00:29:56.270 --> 00:30:00.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is in some sense,
also the simplest observables

00:30:00.770 --> 00:30:03.580 align:middle line:90%
in your theory.

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:04.080 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:07.390 align:middle line:90%
Do you have other questions?

00:30:07.390 --> 00:30:07.960 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:30:07.960 --> 00:30:09.418 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So this
is the correlation

00:30:09.418 --> 00:30:12.570 align:middle line:90%
for the vacuum state, right?

00:30:12.570 --> 00:30:15.276 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, this is the
correlation vacuum state.

00:30:15.276 --> 00:30:19.350 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So you have
a different state?

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:21.850 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, if you're not
in a vacuum state, of course,

00:30:21.850 --> 00:30:23.070 align:middle line:90%
you get a different function.

00:30:23.070 --> 00:30:27.460 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So is there a way
to measure for other states?

00:30:27.460 --> 00:30:29.320 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
you can compute.

00:30:29.320 --> 00:30:33.220 align:middle line:84%
So in this theory, we
can compute in any state.

00:30:33.220 --> 00:30:37.345 align:middle line:84%
But just we often use -- we
probe in the vacuum state.

00:30:37.345 --> 00:30:40.970 align:middle line:90%


00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:42.550 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:30:42.550 --> 00:30:44.140 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, for example,
in the lab, if you

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:46.390 align:middle line:84%
can prepare in
some whatever state

00:30:46.390 --> 00:30:54.060 align:middle line:84%
you prepare, you calculate
this object in that state,

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:55.800 align:middle line:84%
but the vacuum is
the simplest one.

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:56.620 align:middle line:90%
It's the simplest.

00:30:56.620 --> 00:30:57.120 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:30:57.120 --> 00:31:00.096 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]
we can, we can

00:31:00.096 --> 00:31:02.576 align:middle line:84%
define a useful
localized state in space

00:31:02.576 --> 00:31:05.056 align:middle line:84%
and [INAUDIBLE] other
[? state ?] defined

00:31:05.056 --> 00:31:14.000 align:middle line:84%
is also [INAUDIBLE],, spacetime
is useful [INAUDIBLE]??

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.750 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: No, it's
not quite in spacetime.

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:20.230 align:middle line:84%
We will see in what sense
it's approximate to the local

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:20.730 align:middle line:90%
in space.

00:31:20.730 --> 00:31:27.050 align:middle line:90%


00:31:27.050 --> 00:31:27.550 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:31:27.550 --> 00:31:31.950 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's just discuss the
property of those objects.

00:31:31.950 --> 00:31:49.610 align:middle line:84%
And so the first
thing is that the--

00:31:49.610 --> 00:31:52.145 align:middle line:84%
remember the phi satisfy
the following equation.

00:31:52.145 --> 00:31:54.950 align:middle line:90%


00:31:54.950 --> 00:31:59.310 align:middle line:84%
So this is the operating
equation satisfy phi.

00:31:59.310 --> 00:32:06.330 align:middle line:90%
And so if you act this on the--

00:32:06.330 --> 00:32:07.860 align:middle line:90%
so suppose this is--

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:09.870 align:middle line:84%
so here, you have
two arg-- here,

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:12.850 align:middle line:84%
you have two arguments,
x and x prime.

00:32:12.850 --> 00:32:14.730 align:middle line:84%
So here, when we write
differential operator,

00:32:14.730 --> 00:32:16.080 align:middle line:90%
we always refer to x.

00:32:16.080 --> 00:32:19.050 align:middle line:90%
It's always derivative of x.

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:22.070 align:middle line:84%
So we must satisfy
this equation.

00:32:22.070 --> 00:32:25.930 align:middle line:84%
So if you act this on the
G plus and the G minus,

00:32:25.930 --> 00:32:27.670 align:middle line:90%
you immediately get 0.

00:32:27.670 --> 00:32:30.820 align:middle line:84%
So you find-- because
of [INAUDIBLE] equation,

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:35.980 align:middle line:84%
then G plus/minus are just
x and x prime immediately

00:32:35.980 --> 00:32:40.030 align:middle line:84%
gives you 0 just because
phi satisfies this equation.

00:32:40.030 --> 00:32:43.420 align:middle line:84%
Oh, sorry, it should be
a minus sign, I think.

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:45.250 align:middle line:90%
And similarly, with this--

00:32:45.250 --> 00:32:48.218 align:middle line:84%
similarly with delta--
so the delta is

00:32:48.218 --> 00:32:49.510 align:middle line:90%
the difference between the two.

00:32:49.510 --> 00:32:50.680 align:middle line:90%
It's the commutator.

00:32:50.680 --> 00:32:54.595 align:middle line:84%
So the delta is essentially the
difference between G plus and G

00:32:54.595 --> 00:32:57.160 align:middle line:84%
minus, so the same
thing with delta.

00:32:57.160 --> 00:33:15.730 align:middle line:90%


00:33:15.730 --> 00:33:17.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- the
first property is

00:33:17.590 --> 00:33:21.070 align:middle line:84%
that they satisfy
the same equation

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:24.790 align:middle line:84%
as the classical
equations of phi.

00:33:24.790 --> 00:33:26.680 align:middle line:84%
So the G plus and
delta, they satisfy.

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:29.260 align:middle line:90%


00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:30.310 align:middle line:90%
And we will talk--

00:33:30.310 --> 00:34:07.320 align:middle line:84%
and then you can now also
look at the G F and the G R.

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:14.540 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you act this
object on G R, G A, or G F,

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:18.150 align:middle line:84%
the story is a little bit tricky
because the partial square

00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:20.040 align:middle line:90%
containing time derivatives.

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:22.350 align:middle line:84%
And when you add the time
derivatives-- and time

00:34:22.350 --> 00:34:25.415 align:middle line:84%
derivatives do act on
those theta functions.

00:34:25.415 --> 00:34:27.540 align:middle line:84%
And when you add time
derivative on theta function,

00:34:27.540 --> 00:34:30.250 align:middle line:84%
you will get some delta
functions, et cetera.

00:34:30.250 --> 00:34:34.310 align:middle line:84%
And so the story is a
little bit more intricate.

00:34:34.310 --> 00:34:38.219 align:middle line:84%
But if you just
carry it through--

00:34:38.219 --> 00:34:40.940 align:middle line:84%
it just carries through--
then you can show.

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:43.489 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a
simple exercise you

00:34:43.489 --> 00:34:45.020 align:middle line:90%
should try to show yourself--

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:46.699 align:middle line:90%
we'll not do it here--

00:34:46.699 --> 00:34:55.920 align:middle line:84%
that you find, you
act this on the G R A,

00:34:55.920 --> 00:34:59.700 align:middle line:84%
and F. You get actually
the-- any of them,

00:34:59.700 --> 00:35:01.800 align:middle line:90%
you get the same equation.

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:04.710 align:middle line:84%
You get the right-hand
side becomes--

00:35:04.710 --> 00:35:08.770 align:middle line:84%
it's non-zero-- actually
gives you a delta function.

00:35:08.770 --> 00:35:10.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is a four-dimensional
delta function.

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:13.155 align:middle line:84%
So in both in spatial
location and in time.

00:35:13.155 --> 00:35:19.520 align:middle line:90%


00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:21.340 align:middle line:84%
So heuristically,
you can understand

00:35:21.340 --> 00:35:24.530 align:middle line:84%
that this delta
function in time comes

00:35:24.530 --> 00:35:31.670 align:middle line:84%
from taking derivative
on theta functions

00:35:31.670 --> 00:35:40.330 align:middle line:84%
and then the derivative
in the spatial direction--

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:43.330 align:middle line:84%
oh, delta function in
the spatial direction

00:35:43.330 --> 00:35:46.190 align:middle line:84%
can come out in
the following way.

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:48.590 align:middle line:90%
So here, you have two--

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:50.360 align:middle line:84%
so here, you have
two time derivatives

00:35:50.360 --> 00:35:51.890 align:middle line:90%
right in the partial square.

00:35:51.890 --> 00:35:56.000 align:middle line:84%
So imagine you have one time
derivative acting on the theta

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.910 align:middle line:84%
function, and then give you
a delta function in time.

00:35:58.910 --> 00:36:03.860 align:middle line:84%
And then if you have one time
derivative acting on this phi,

00:36:03.860 --> 00:36:06.510 align:middle line:90%
and then taking it into pi.

00:36:06.510 --> 00:36:09.300 align:middle line:84%
And then equal time
commutator then

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:13.110 align:middle line:84%
give you a delta function
in the spatial direction,

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:16.370 align:middle line:90%
and so that's how you get that.

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:19.700 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, but it's easy
to check yourself.

00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:21.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
property-- is that they

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:23.370 align:middle line:90%
satisfy those nice equations.

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:26.170 align:middle line:90%


00:36:26.170 --> 00:36:32.560 align:middle line:84%
The second property is
that phi x and phi x prime,

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:35.110 align:middle line:84%
even though in general
they don't commute,

00:36:35.110 --> 00:36:46.110 align:middle line:84%
but they actually commute
for space-like separations.

00:36:46.110 --> 00:36:51.420 align:middle line:90%


00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:55.190 align:middle line:84%
So that means that if you
look at the commutator of phi

00:36:55.190 --> 00:36:59.040 align:middle line:84%
x and phi x prime,
this is actually

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:06.220 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0 for x minus x prime
greater than square greater

00:37:06.220 --> 00:37:10.170 align:middle line:84%
than 0 for space-like
separations.

00:37:10.170 --> 00:37:14.160 align:middle line:90%


00:37:14.160 --> 00:37:17.680 align:middle line:84%
So this can be checked by
expression computation.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:20.130 align:middle line:84%
So we know the mode
expression of phi.

00:37:20.130 --> 00:37:22.370 align:middle line:90%
You can just do it commutator--

00:37:22.370 --> 00:37:25.140 align:middle line:90%
yeah, you can just check it.

00:37:25.140 --> 00:37:26.910 align:middle line:90%
But you can also--

00:37:26.910 --> 00:37:29.640 align:middle line:84%
but there's also a simple
argument to make it.

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:33.200 align:middle line:90%


00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:39.590 align:middle line:84%
So you can do-- you can check
by expression computation.

00:37:39.590 --> 00:37:46.790 align:middle line:90%


00:37:46.790 --> 00:37:48.695 align:middle line:84%
So here, I give you
alternative argument.

00:37:48.695 --> 00:37:56.310 align:middle line:90%


00:37:56.310 --> 00:37:59.640 align:middle line:84%
Here, I give you an
alternative derivation.

00:37:59.640 --> 00:38:05.650 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, it's very simple,
but let me just divide it

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:07.615 align:middle line:90%
into three small steps.

00:38:07.615 --> 00:38:10.480 align:middle line:90%


00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:13.910 align:middle line:90%
So essentially, by definition--

00:38:13.910 --> 00:38:15.490 align:middle line:84%
so let's just
consider-- yeah, we

00:38:15.490 --> 00:38:19.840 align:middle line:84%
consider the commutator, which
here we call to be delta.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:22.850 align:middle line:90%
So the delta x plus/minus--

00:38:22.850 --> 00:38:25.570 align:middle line:84%
oh, x and x prime,
which is the commutator.

00:38:25.570 --> 00:38:28.210 align:middle line:90%


00:38:28.210 --> 00:38:30.010 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let me define--

00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:34.090 align:middle line:84%
yeah, sorry--
yeah, so delta here

00:38:34.090 --> 00:38:39.550 align:middle line:84%
is the expectation value of 0,
so let me call this delta hat.

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:41.980 align:middle line:84%
So the delta hat is defined
to be the commutator.

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:49.790 align:middle line:90%


00:38:49.790 --> 00:38:52.490 align:middle line:84%
So the first claim is that
this is actually a C number.

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:57.520 align:middle line:90%


00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:03.070 align:middle line:84%
So this is C number, and
the reason is very simple.

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:06.960 align:middle line:84%
So just some constant-- even if
it's non-zero can, at the most,

00:39:06.960 --> 00:39:08.670 align:middle line:90%
be a constant.

00:39:08.670 --> 00:39:10.650 align:middle line:84%
Be some-- yeah,
but C number means

00:39:10.650 --> 00:39:14.490 align:middle line:90%
that it's not an operator.

00:39:14.490 --> 00:39:16.530 align:middle line:84%
So the reason this
is C number is

00:39:16.530 --> 00:39:21.090 align:middle line:84%
because if you look at the phi,
it's linear in a and a dagger.

00:39:21.090 --> 00:39:25.410 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the commutator
between phi and phi itself,

00:39:25.410 --> 00:39:28.980 align:middle line:84%
you always just get commuted
between a and a dagger.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:32.490 align:middle line:84%
a and a dagger just
give you a constant,

00:39:32.490 --> 00:39:37.280 align:middle line:84%
and so this just--
you get some C number.

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:43.160 align:middle line:84%
So in fact-- so this delta hat
is actually the same as delta

00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:44.760 align:middle line:84%
because the, if
your C number, you

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:46.760 align:middle line:84%
take this expectation
value doesn't do anything.

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:49.470 align:middle line:90%


00:39:49.470 --> 00:39:56.010 align:middle line:84%
So the second step is that
now let's consider the Lorentz

00:39:56.010 --> 00:39:57.810 align:middle line:90%
transformation--

00:39:57.810 --> 00:40:02.190 align:middle line:84%
the operator, which generates
the Lorentz transformation,

00:40:02.190 --> 00:40:04.460 align:middle line:90%
which is given by--

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:06.810 align:middle line:84%
remember, we
discussed last time.

00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:11.220 align:middle line:90%


00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:13.520 align:middle line:90%
So this is the generator.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:16.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is the unitary--
so this is operator

00:40:16.900 --> 00:40:19.069 align:middle line:90%
of Lorentz transformation.

00:40:19.069 --> 00:40:25.670 align:middle line:90%


00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:29.770 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at this object.

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:31.330 align:middle line:90%
And then by definition--

00:40:31.330 --> 00:40:34.120 align:middle line:90%


00:40:34.120 --> 00:40:40.800 align:middle line:84%
so this object acting
on phi x dagger

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:44.250 align:middle line:90%
will give you phi prime x.

00:40:44.250 --> 00:40:47.340 align:middle line:84%
And phi prime x transforms
phi under the Lorentz

00:40:47.340 --> 00:40:48.840 align:middle line:84%
transformation, and
this is the same

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:52.600 align:middle line:84%
as you just do an
inverse Lorentz transform

00:40:52.600 --> 00:40:54.250 align:middle line:90%
on the coordinates.

00:40:54.250 --> 00:40:57.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is the--

00:40:57.420 --> 00:40:59.730 align:middle line:90%
so by the way, just--

00:40:59.730 --> 00:41:03.340 align:middle line:84%
do you feel comfortable
about this equation?

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:06.080 align:middle line:84%
Do you know where this
equation comes from?

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:07.580 align:middle line:84%
So you're all
comfortable with this?

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:08.180 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:15.110 align:middle line:90%


00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:19.100 align:middle line:84%
So by definition, U
acts on phi as this.

00:41:19.100 --> 00:41:21.560 align:middle line:90%
So now, let's just act both--

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:25.835 align:middle line:84%
act U and U lambda dagger on
both sides of this equation.

00:41:25.835 --> 00:41:32.800 align:middle line:90%


00:41:32.800 --> 00:41:35.240 align:middle line:90%
And then we get--

00:41:35.240 --> 00:41:37.320 align:middle line:90%
so on the right-hand side--

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:41.990 align:middle line:84%
so this is a unitary operator
-- because the M is Hermitian,

00:41:41.990 --> 00:41:43.370 align:middle line:90%
this is a unitary operator.

00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.100 align:middle line:84%
So the right-hand side, you
just go back to this C number.

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:47.900 align:middle line:90%
It does not change.

00:41:47.900 --> 00:41:49.670 align:middle line:90%
So the equation does not change.

00:41:49.670 --> 00:41:53.250 align:middle line:90%
And the left-hand side--

00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:56.270 align:middle line:90%
so the delta is the same.

00:41:56.270 --> 00:41:57.875 align:middle line:90%
So you find that the--

00:41:57.875 --> 00:42:01.100 align:middle line:90%


00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:06.020 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so you find the
delta x prime, which

00:42:06.020 --> 00:42:07.400 align:middle line:90%
is equal to this C number.

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:14.330 align:middle line:84%
Then, it's the same as
U Lambda phi x phi x

00:42:14.330 --> 00:42:18.050 align:middle line:90%
prime and the U lambda dagger.

00:42:18.050 --> 00:42:22.410 align:middle line:84%
And that gives
you-- me phi lambda

00:42:22.410 --> 00:42:27.810 align:middle line:84%
minus 1 x commutator with phi
lambda 1-- minus 1 x prime.

00:42:27.810 --> 00:42:31.140 align:middle line:84%
So that's the same
as delta lambda

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:33.240 align:middle line:90%
x and the lambda x prime.

00:42:33.240 --> 00:43:09.590 align:middle line:90%


00:43:09.590 --> 00:43:10.970 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:43:10.970 --> 00:43:16.170 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can look
at the last step.

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:19.730 align:middle line:84%
So you see, when we make
a Lorentz transformation

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:22.580 align:middle line:84%
on delta, actually
nothing changes,

