And so here, you just get
k squared plus m squared.

01:12:35.390 --> 01:12:39.290 align:middle line:84%
And let me just call it
G, so denote any of them,

01:12:39.290 --> 01:12:42.260 align:middle line:90%
equal to minus i.

01:12:42.260 --> 01:12:44.100 align:middle line:84%
Because the
right-hand side, when

01:12:44.100 --> 01:12:46.100 align:middle line:84%
you do a Fourier transform,
it just becomes one.

01:12:46.100 --> 01:12:47.700 align:middle line:90%
It's a delta function.

01:12:47.700 --> 01:12:51.840 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can immediately
write down the expression

01:12:51.840 --> 01:12:52.700 align:middle line:90%
in momentum space.

01:12:52.700 --> 01:13:03.090 align:middle line:90%


01:13:03.090 --> 01:13:06.460 align:middle line:84%
But now, you see
we have a problem.

01:13:06.460 --> 01:13:10.240 align:middle line:90%
So what problem do we have?

01:13:10.240 --> 01:13:11.290 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:11.290 --> 01:13:14.050 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: When you have k squared
equals negative m squared

01:13:14.050 --> 01:13:15.850 align:middle line:90%
it's like a singularity.

01:13:15.850 --> 01:13:16.930 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Good.

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:19.338 align:middle line:90%
Well, we have a lot of problems.

01:13:19.338 --> 01:13:20.630 align:middle line:90%
So this is one of the problems.

01:13:20.630 --> 01:13:21.635 align:middle line:90%
We have another problem.

01:13:21.635 --> 01:13:22.565 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:22.565 --> 01:13:23.960 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Is this on shell?

01:13:23.960 --> 01:13:24.593 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Hmm?

01:13:24.593 --> 01:13:26.958 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:26.958 --> 01:13:29.800 align:middle line:90%


01:13:29.800 --> 01:13:31.780 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So k is not
on shell, because when

01:13:31.780 --> 01:13:36.910 align:middle line:84%
we do a Fourier transform,
it's for the general k.

01:13:36.910 --> 01:13:39.370 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's defined
for the general k.

01:13:39.370 --> 01:13:40.990 align:middle line:84%
Indeed, for the on
shell value of k,

01:13:40.990 --> 01:13:43.165 align:middle line:84%
then you will have
a singular behavior.

01:13:43.165 --> 01:13:45.680 align:middle line:90%


01:13:45.680 --> 01:13:48.380 align:middle line:84%
But for the-- but we still
have another problem.

01:13:48.380 --> 01:13:57.410 align:middle line:90%


01:13:57.410 --> 01:13:58.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:58.060 --> 01:14:00.910 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: They're not
supposed to be complex?

01:14:00.910 --> 01:14:02.230 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it is complex.

01:14:02.230 --> 01:14:04.580 align:middle line:90%
It's OK.

01:14:04.580 --> 01:14:06.050 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that aspect is OK.

01:14:06.050 --> 01:14:07.445 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so since--

01:14:07.445 --> 01:14:08.810 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

01:14:08.810 --> 01:14:15.900 align:middle line:84%
So you see here, we have defined
the three different functions,

01:14:15.900 --> 01:14:19.281 align:middle line:84%
but there, how many
solutions we have?

01:14:19.281 --> 01:14:20.160 align:middle line:90%
We only have one.

01:14:20.160 --> 01:14:22.380 align:middle line:84%
We have unique
solution seems like.

01:14:22.380 --> 01:14:24.635 align:middle line:90%
Then we have a problem.

01:14:24.635 --> 01:14:26.010 align:middle line:84%
It seems like--
that seems to say

01:14:26.010 --> 01:14:27.218 align:middle line:90%
all these three are the same.

01:14:27.218 --> 01:14:31.080 align:middle line:84%
But if you calculate them
going through this theta

01:14:31.080 --> 01:14:35.310 align:middle line:84%
function [INAUDIBLE],,
they are not the same.

01:14:35.310 --> 01:14:37.670 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out these
two problems are related.

01:14:37.670 --> 01:14:40.205 align:middle line:90%


01:14:40.205 --> 01:14:43.320 align:middle line:84%
It turns out these two problems
are related because now,

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:47.790 align:middle line:84%
if you consider the coordinate
space expression, which

01:14:47.790 --> 01:14:50.145 align:middle line:84%
obtained by the Fourier
transform of this guy--

01:14:50.145 --> 01:15:01.070 align:middle line:90%


01:15:01.070 --> 01:15:04.180 align:middle line:84%
again, by Fourier
transform of this guy--

01:15:04.180 --> 01:15:12.410 align:middle line:84%
so in the-- so if you write
down explicitly 1 over k squared

01:15:12.410 --> 01:15:14.300 align:middle line:90%
plus--

01:15:14.300 --> 01:15:17.670 align:middle line:84%
so 1 over k squared
plus m squared,

01:15:17.670 --> 01:15:19.020 align:middle line:90%
if we write it explicitly.

01:15:19.020 --> 01:15:24.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1 over minus omega
squared plus k squared plus m

01:15:24.140 --> 01:15:25.670 align:middle line:90%
squared--

01:15:25.670 --> 01:15:26.910 align:middle line:90%
write it explicitly.

01:15:26.910 --> 01:15:30.020 align:middle line:84%
And then this is
equal to minus omega

01:15:30.020 --> 01:15:33.380 align:middle line:90%
squared plus omega k squared.

01:15:33.380 --> 01:15:35.015 align:middle line:84%
So this is just the
omega k squared.

01:15:35.015 --> 01:15:37.970 align:middle line:90%


01:15:37.970 --> 01:15:43.040 align:middle line:84%
So as you said, this actually
has a singularity when omega

01:15:43.040 --> 01:15:45.040 align:middle line:90%
equal to plus minus omega k.

01:15:45.040 --> 01:15:49.330 align:middle line:84%
When you satisfy this
on shell condition.

01:15:49.330 --> 01:15:53.680 align:middle line:84%
But this singularity is actually
along the integration contour

01:15:53.680 --> 01:15:54.190 align:middle line:90%
of omega.

01:15:54.190 --> 01:15:56.850 align:middle line:90%


01:15:56.850 --> 01:16:03.190 align:middle line:84%
Because in these four integrals
is given by d omega dk.

01:16:03.190 --> 01:16:06.730 align:middle line:84%
So the omega-- so this
from minus infinity

01:16:06.730 --> 01:16:08.790 align:middle line:90%
to plus infinity.

01:16:08.790 --> 01:16:12.330 align:middle line:84%
And these two singularities
are the real value of omega.

01:16:12.330 --> 01:16:18.080 align:middle line:84%
So they actually-- so if
you look at omega axis--

01:16:18.080 --> 01:16:21.190 align:middle line:84%
so at these two points,
actually, they become singular.

01:16:21.190 --> 01:16:25.730 align:middle line:90%
The integrand is singular.

01:16:25.730 --> 01:16:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So the integral is
actually not well-defined.

01:16:29.340 --> 01:16:31.620 align:middle line:84%
So the integral is
not well-defined.

01:16:31.620 --> 01:16:35.020 align:middle line:84%
So in order to
define the integral--

01:16:35.020 --> 01:16:38.320 align:middle line:84%
in order to define
this omega integral,

01:16:38.320 --> 01:16:45.250 align:middle line:84%
then we have to do your standard
trick in complex analysis.

01:16:45.250 --> 01:16:47.690 align:middle line:90%
So what is that trick?

01:16:47.690 --> 01:16:48.470 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:16:48.470 --> 01:16:50.120 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:50.120 --> 01:16:51.120 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:16:51.120 --> 01:16:55.150 align:middle line:90%
You go around the singularity.

01:16:55.150 --> 01:16:58.940 align:middle line:84%
So now, you go to
the complex plane--

01:16:58.940 --> 01:17:00.290 align:middle line:90%
complex omega plane.

01:17:00.290 --> 01:17:02.930 align:middle line:90%
So now this is a real omega.

01:17:02.930 --> 01:17:04.400 align:middle line:90%
This is imaginary omega.

01:17:04.400 --> 01:17:05.960 align:middle line:84%
You go to the
complex omega plane.

01:17:05.960 --> 01:17:09.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, the integration constant
is along the real axis.

01:17:09.390 --> 01:17:12.900 align:middle line:84%
And now, you have four
different choices.

01:17:12.900 --> 01:17:19.040 align:middle line:84%
You can either go up or going
down for each one of them.

01:17:19.040 --> 01:17:21.030 align:middle line:84%
And now you have four
different choices.

01:17:21.030 --> 01:17:25.420 align:middle line:84%
And this 3 equals 1 into
three choices of them.

01:17:25.420 --> 01:17:28.530 align:middle line:84%
Then there's a fourth one,
which is not frequently used,

01:17:28.530 --> 01:17:30.920 align:middle line:84%
so we normally don't
give them a name.

01:17:30.920 --> 01:17:34.160 align:middle line:84%
And the fourth one, sometimes,
we call them G F tilde.

01:17:34.160 --> 01:17:38.150 align:middle line:84%
It's just-- anyway, so there are
four different choices of going

01:17:38.150 --> 01:17:41.540 align:middle line:84%
around the singularity,
and then that gives you

01:17:41.540 --> 01:17:44.930 align:middle line:90%
four possible solutions.

01:17:44.930 --> 01:17:47.421 align:middle line:90%
And then that gives you the--

01:17:47.421 --> 01:17:51.300 align:middle line:90%


01:17:51.300 --> 01:17:54.540 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so now let's
talk about the G R--

01:17:54.540 --> 01:17:56.500 align:middle line:90%
do them one by one.

01:17:56.500 --> 01:17:59.430 align:middle line:90%
So for G R--

01:17:59.430 --> 01:18:03.120 align:middle line:84%
so remember, G R
is defined to be

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:06.360 align:middle line:84%
when theta t greater
than t prime,

01:18:06.360 --> 01:18:10.420 align:middle line:84%
G R should be proportional
to t, to t minus t prime.

01:18:10.420 --> 01:18:16.580 align:middle line:84%
So that means this should
be 0 for t minus t prime

01:18:16.580 --> 01:18:17.390 align:middle line:90%
smaller than 0.

01:18:17.390 --> 01:18:19.910 align:middle line:90%


01:18:19.910 --> 01:18:25.090 align:middle line:84%
This should be 0 for t minus
t prime smaller than 0.

01:18:25.090 --> 01:18:30.370 align:middle line:84%
So how do we achieve that
by going around the poles?

01:18:30.370 --> 01:18:35.500 align:middle line:84%
So remember, in this
integral, it's a peice minus--

01:18:35.500 --> 01:18:41.180 align:middle line:84%
the omega dependent piece is
minus i omega t minus t prime.

01:18:41.180 --> 01:18:43.970 align:middle line:84%
So when t minus t
prime smaller than 0.

01:18:43.970 --> 01:18:48.630 align:middle line:84%
If you want to do this integral
using contour integration,

01:18:48.630 --> 01:18:50.810 align:middle line:90%
then you can close--

01:18:50.810 --> 01:18:53.353 align:middle line:84%
so this is smaller than 0,
and then this is positive.

01:18:53.353 --> 01:18:55.520 align:middle line:84%
And then you can close the
contour in the upper half

01:18:55.520 --> 01:18:56.960 align:middle line:90%
plane.

01:18:56.960 --> 01:18:59.330 align:middle line:84%
You can close the contour
in the upper half plane.

01:18:59.330 --> 01:19:02.090 align:middle line:84%
In order for this
to be identically 0,

01:19:02.090 --> 01:19:04.550 align:middle line:84%
you need your
integration-- counter

01:19:04.550 --> 01:19:06.830 align:middle line:90%
don't enclose any singularity.

01:19:06.830 --> 01:19:11.690 align:middle line:84%
So that means for
the retarded, you

01:19:11.690 --> 01:19:14.360 align:middle line:84%
need to going around the
singularity along which

01:19:14.360 --> 01:19:15.020 align:middle line:90%
direction?

01:19:15.020 --> 01:19:18.150 align:middle line:90%


01:19:18.150 --> 01:19:19.826 align:middle line:90%
We only have one minute left.

01:19:19.826 --> 01:19:22.060 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:22.060 --> 01:19:24.550 align:middle line:84%
For it to be 0, when
you integrate-- so

01:19:24.550 --> 01:19:27.940 align:middle line:84%
you want to close in
the upper half plane.

01:19:27.940 --> 01:19:31.030 align:middle line:84%
You want to close it
because the t minus t prime

01:19:31.030 --> 01:19:34.110 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than 0, and then this
is positive i, and the omega

01:19:34.110 --> 01:19:35.110 align:middle line:90%
in the upper half plane.

01:19:35.110 --> 01:19:37.490 align:middle line:90%
This is a decay exponential.

01:19:37.490 --> 01:19:41.690 align:middle line:84%
And so you wonder, there's no
singularity inside the contour,

01:19:41.690 --> 01:19:46.700 align:middle line:84%
and then you want to go around
the singularity this way.

01:19:46.700 --> 01:19:49.400 align:middle line:90%
Going above the singularity.

01:19:49.400 --> 01:19:51.920 align:middle line:84%
When you're going above
the singularity, and then

01:19:51.920 --> 01:19:53.970 align:middle line:90%
this contour don't include--

01:19:53.970 --> 01:19:57.350 align:middle line:90%
and then within this contour--

01:19:57.350 --> 01:19:58.730 align:middle line:90%
and then there's no singularity.

01:19:58.730 --> 01:20:01.790 align:middle line:84%
Then, this is identically
0 from the Cauchy theorem.

01:20:01.790 --> 01:20:04.820 align:middle line:84%
So it tells you that for
the retarded Green function,

01:20:04.820 --> 01:20:08.640 align:middle line:90%
you need the contour like that.

01:20:08.640 --> 01:20:15.450 align:middle line:90%
So similarly, for the advanced--

01:20:15.450 --> 01:20:19.090 align:middle line:84%
because the advanced, we
just change the direction.

01:20:19.090 --> 01:20:21.300 align:middle line:90%
So this is for the retarded.

01:20:21.300 --> 01:20:26.200 align:middle line:84%
For the advanced,
it's proportional to t

01:20:26.200 --> 01:20:26.898 align:middle line:90%
minus t prime.

01:20:26.898 --> 01:20:28.690 align:middle line:84%
Then you just go in
the opposite direction.

01:20:28.690 --> 01:20:31.870 align:middle line:90%


01:20:31.870 --> 01:20:35.410 align:middle line:84%
So this is for the
retarded-- for the advanced.

01:20:35.410 --> 01:20:41.070 align:middle line:84%
And then, finally, if we want
to do it for the Feynman--

01:20:41.070 --> 01:20:43.800 align:middle line:84%
and then you choose
one of them going up

01:20:43.800 --> 01:20:44.940 align:middle line:90%
and one of them going down.

01:20:44.940 --> 01:20:48.030 align:middle line:84%
I always forget which one
going up, which one going down.

01:20:48.030 --> 01:20:52.920 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so actually, this one
you go down, and this one you

01:20:52.920 --> 01:20:54.240 align:middle line:90%
go up.

01:20:54.240 --> 01:21:04.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is for the Feynman for
the G F. That's all for today.

01:21:04.140 --> 01:21:08.000 align:middle line:90%